Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.844
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.844 --> 00:00:07.060
SPEAKER 1: Welcome, everyone.

00:00:07.060 --> 00:00:12.150
We are so excited to
host Gonzalo Guzman, chef

00:00:12.150 --> 00:00:14.010
and partner of
Nopalito restaurant,

00:00:14.010 --> 00:00:16.239
and his co-author of
the beautiful Nopalito

00:00:16.239 --> 00:00:17.840
book, Stacy Adimondo.

00:00:17.840 --> 00:00:20.140
SPEAKER 2: Thank
you, [? Elia. ?]

00:00:20.140 --> 00:00:22.370
So first question
I have is I want

00:00:22.370 --> 00:00:25.520
to know what was your
first exposure to cooking.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:29.235
GONZALO GUZMAN: When I met
actually Chef Laurence, chef,

00:00:29.235 --> 00:00:32.380
owner of Nopa right now.

00:00:32.380 --> 00:00:37.900
So I just came to his
kitchen, and just started

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:39.430
seeing a bunch of
things going on.

00:00:39.430 --> 00:00:42.250
And they were all just
pretty attractive to me,

00:00:42.250 --> 00:00:48.300
so I just decided that that's
kind of what I wanted to do.

00:00:48.300 --> 00:00:53.050
Because before that, I just
started working in restaurants.

00:00:53.050 --> 00:00:53.800
It was just a job.

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:55.424
It wasn't something
that I wanted to do

00:00:55.424 --> 00:00:58.066
or something that
was in my head.

00:00:58.066 --> 00:00:59.920
But after seeing
all that, I realized

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.711
that that's something
that I kind of wanted

00:01:01.711 --> 00:01:04.140
to take serious and start--

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:05.920
yes, start taking more serious.

00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:09.390
And just start cooking and see
where that was going to go.

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:13.829
SPEAKER 2: Did you have
previous experience before that?

00:01:13.829 --> 00:01:14.620
GONZALO GUZMAN: No.

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:19.335
I started as most people
when they first come here,

00:01:19.335 --> 00:01:21.820
washing dishes, which I
did in another restaurant

00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:23.770
for like probably
a couple of months.

00:01:23.770 --> 00:01:27.640
And then they put me right
away into a prep station,

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:30.280
and then a few months
later, I was line cook.

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:32.650
And then I started
working all the stations

00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:36.070
in that restaurant,
and that's kind of how

00:01:36.070 --> 00:01:39.131
I learned what I now know.

00:01:39.131 --> 00:01:41.620
STACY ADIMONDO: One thing that's
pretty neat that Laurence,

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:45.010
the co-owner of Nopalito, says
in his introduction to the book

00:01:45.010 --> 00:01:48.610
is that a lot of
Mexican immigrants

00:01:48.610 --> 00:01:50.080
had come through his kitchens.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.990
And not all of them fall
in love with cooking.

00:01:52.990 --> 00:01:54.970
And he said he really
saw something special

00:01:54.970 --> 00:01:57.730
in Gonzalo, in
that from day one,

00:01:57.730 --> 00:01:59.650
he had wide eyes and
a lot of curiosity.

00:01:59.650 --> 00:02:02.380
And he was really
excited to get into it

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:03.850
as a career and
a lifetime thing,

00:02:03.850 --> 00:02:06.010
rather than just
a quick way to get

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:08.600
himself settled in the
country and make some money.

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:12.132
So that was, I think,
what inspired Laurence

00:02:12.132 --> 00:02:14.590
to kind of say, I'm going to
keep this guy around and teach

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:15.580
him a few things.

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:17.121
GONZALO GUZMAN: And
I was also raised

00:02:17.121 --> 00:02:19.250
by my mom and two
sisters, so all women.

00:02:19.250 --> 00:02:21.260
So I kind of had to--
since I was little,

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:26.440
I remember doing all these
things that normally are just

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:27.700
for women in Mexico.

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:31.930
The place that I was
born in, South Mexico.

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:34.390
So, again, growing
in that kind of--

00:02:34.390 --> 00:02:39.330
seeing all these-- the
way my mom was preparing,

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:41.920
and going into the garden and
picking all these vegetables

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:45.334
and all that, it was in my--

00:02:45.334 --> 00:02:46.500
I guess, in my life already.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:47.916
So it's not somebody
that I wanted

00:02:47.916 --> 00:02:50.540
to do forever at that moment.

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:53.565
But then it's always been
with me since I was--

00:02:53.565 --> 00:02:55.035
since I remember.

00:02:55.035 --> 00:02:56.410
SPEAKER 2: So is
that kind of how

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:57.909
you developed your
style of cooking,

00:02:57.909 --> 00:03:01.040
is through cooking with your
family and all that stuff?

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:04.137
And then you got more trained
when you came here and started

00:03:04.137 --> 00:03:05.095
working in restaurants?

00:03:05.095 --> 00:03:05.970
GONZALO GUZMAN: Yeah.

00:03:05.970 --> 00:03:10.830
After like 10 years, I guess,
before we opened Nopalito,

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:13.780
I worked in so many
different restaurants here

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:16.900
in San Francisco.

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:18.850
But in the back of
my head, I always

00:03:18.850 --> 00:03:23.410
had that idea of doing something
with Mexican food, which

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:26.740
that's the food that
I was raised with.

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:30.100
But always doing everything
that way I was raised with too.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:33.610
And what I mean by
that is we will dry--

00:03:33.610 --> 00:03:35.170
or plant our own
corn and dry it.

00:03:35.170 --> 00:03:37.510
And then we will cook it,
and then we will grind it.

00:03:37.510 --> 00:03:41.060
So pretty much everything
from scratch, and that's

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:43.250
kind of what I wanted
to do if I ever

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:45.290
will do Mexican food
or a Mexican-based kind

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:46.280
of restaurant.

00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:48.280
STACY ADIMONDO: I also
think one of the baffling

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:51.160
things about making Nopalito
work from the beginning

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:54.490
was that he had such a
high standard of that.

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:57.220
It wasn't just, we're going
to grab tomatoes and make

00:03:57.220 --> 00:04:00.610
a fresh tomato salsa,
because everybody expects it

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:01.860
to be at a Mexican restaurant.

00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:04.026
He sort of thought, well,
tomatoes aren't in-season,

00:04:04.026 --> 00:04:05.710
so why would I use
them in the salsa?

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:10.350
So they kind of operate the
same way that they would--

00:04:10.350 --> 00:04:12.630
that Gonzalo did when
he was growing up.

00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:14.110
Where, literally,
what was around

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:17.470
was chopped down off a tree
or picked out of the ground.

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:19.751
And that was the way
they liked to cook,

00:04:19.751 --> 00:04:21.459
and it was a way that
made sense to cook.

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:23.580
So I think he's maintained
that in Nopalito,

00:04:23.580 --> 00:04:25.420
but at such a large scale.

00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:27.610
They have two restaurants.

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:30.810
How many pounds of masa come
out of the kitchen every day?

00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:32.530
GONZALO GUZMAN: Between
both restaurants,

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:36.760
I think we do between 200 and
300 pounds of corn every day.

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:40.480
STACY ADIMONDO: And it's all
organic corn, if possible,

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:44.410
grown locally in
California and outside.

00:04:44.410 --> 00:04:47.620
That's a serious undertaking
to even find that much product,

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:50.080
and do that by hand
just to start the day.

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:52.460
That's with every single
element of the Nopalito cooking,

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:54.940
is something that's
grown in-season,

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:56.770
locally, and the
best possible product

00:04:56.770 --> 00:04:58.080
that they could've found.

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:00.090
SPEAKER 2: Yeah, and there's a--

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:02.890
your appetizer,
the garbanzo beans.

00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:05.720
You said they was traditionally
done with peanuts, but--

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:07.411
GONZALO GUZMAN:
Well, again, just--

00:05:07.411 --> 00:05:07.910
it's funny.

00:05:07.910 --> 00:05:10.160
I grew up in a really,
really small community.

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:11.470
400 people.

00:05:11.470 --> 00:05:14.690
No electricity, no
water when I was there.

00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:18.740
So again, my dad and
my mom, sometimes when

00:05:18.740 --> 00:05:23.090
they wanted to spend some
time in the family together,

00:05:23.090 --> 00:05:26.680
they will just fry some
peanuts from our fields.

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:28.680
And they will just fry
them with chili and lime,

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:31.310
and that was kind
of like our dinner

00:05:31.310 --> 00:05:33.824
sometimes, because
there was nothing else.

00:05:33.824 --> 00:05:35.990
But that's kind like the
idea of the garbanzos came.

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:38.450
And also because we wanted to
offer something to the guests

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:42.040
when they will first
arrive to the restaurant.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:46.780
We didn't want to do
chips and guacamole,

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:51.510
or salsas that most Mexican
restaurants or taquerias

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:52.310
do here.

00:05:52.310 --> 00:05:54.140
We wanted to give it more like--

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:54.890
original, I guess.

00:05:54.890 --> 00:05:58.160
The way I was raised,
but also give something

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:01.360
to kind of start
water their mouth

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:05.444
and start ordering
more drinks too.

00:06:05.444 --> 00:06:06.141
I was still--

00:06:06.141 --> 00:06:07.640
STACY ADIMONDO: And
the peanuts were

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:10.622
very difficult to find
organically in the quantities

00:06:10.622 --> 00:06:11.330
that they wanted.

00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:13.730
So he thought, how do I get
creative with something that

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:15.710
does make sense year-round?

00:06:15.710 --> 00:06:17.540
And so he picked
chickpeas, fried

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:21.246
like as to mimic that crunchy,
little nutty kind of snack.

00:06:21.246 --> 00:06:23.510
GONZALO GUZMAN: So
my idea is different.

00:06:23.510 --> 00:06:26.030
SPEAKER 2: So you've
mentioned restaurants

00:06:26.030 --> 00:06:27.920
you've tried when
you first moved here,

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:33.260
and you even just did air quotes
to signify Mexican restaurants.

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:36.980
What was your first thoughts
about Mexican restaurants

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:40.445
when you first moved?

00:06:40.445 --> 00:06:42.960
GONZALO GUZMAN: To me, I
thought it was Mexican food,

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:47.120
but for a bunch of
other Mexican people.

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:50.060
Because the way I
was raised, again, it

00:06:50.060 --> 00:06:53.800
was totally different of what
I saw here in restaurants.

00:06:53.800 --> 00:06:57.867
Like corn tortilla tasted like
plastic to me, to be honest.

00:06:57.867 --> 00:06:59.450
I was used to really
tasting the corn.

00:06:59.450 --> 00:07:01.670
I was used to taste
the ingredient.

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:05.480
Something that I felt like
I couldn't really find here,

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:08.360
I will go to taquerias
or restaurants.

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:11.570
And I will order
this sope, which

00:07:11.570 --> 00:07:13.970
is pretty similar to
a traditional dish

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:17.050
that my mom will do when I
was little, called picadita.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:19.500
About the same idea, but
usually they're thin and--

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:28.460
thicker than a tortilla, but
thinner than the sope tortilla.

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:30.560
And when I first
tasted that, because it

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:33.820
was the closest that I could
remember to my hometown,

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:34.820
I didn't like it at all.

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:37.660
It was really doughy and it
didn't really taste like corn.

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:39.860
It taste like
Play-Doh or something.

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:42.100
So again, I just went
between restaurants

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:44.570
and I just couldn't
really find anything

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:47.942
that I felt like it
was Mexican food to me.

00:07:47.942 --> 00:07:49.418
Yeah.

00:07:49.418 --> 00:07:52.250
SPEAKER 2: So you
had a long process

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:56.175
of actually becoming Head Chef
of Nopalito and all that stuff.

00:07:56.175 --> 00:07:58.550
I do want to read something,
because I do love your book.

00:07:58.550 --> 00:08:01.720
And you said, "Mexican
food, at heart,

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:03.560
is a labor-intensive
style of cuisine

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:05.300
from a hardworking people."

00:08:05.300 --> 00:08:08.470
So how did you get
to where you're

00:08:08.470 --> 00:08:11.216
at from where you started?

00:08:11.216 --> 00:08:13.880
GONZALO GUZMAN: You hear
these people saying,

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:16.820
work smarter instead of harder.

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:19.370
But I think if you combine
those two, you just kind of like

00:08:19.370 --> 00:08:21.860
rush everything in a good way.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:23.930
And to me, it was
like working hard.

00:08:23.930 --> 00:08:25.540
Like working two
jobs in the morning,

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:27.290
at night, because I
knew I couldn't really

00:08:27.290 --> 00:08:28.484
go to culinary school.

00:08:28.484 --> 00:08:29.900
And first of all,
because I didn't

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:32.340
speak any English at all.

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:37.490
And second of all, because I
had to pay back a lot of money.

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:40.039
But I also wanted to learn more
different type of cuisines,

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:42.506
and that's why I went back
and forth between restaurants.

00:08:42.506 --> 00:08:44.630
Because I felt like that
was kind of like, I will--

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:47.360
that was my way to
just learn something

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:51.164
that I wasn't able to learn
from not going to school.

00:08:51.164 --> 00:08:53.580
So I was working always really
hard, but at the same time,

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:57.200
I was also taking some ESL
classes at city college

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:01.280
here just to learn the
language as much as I could.

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:04.580
Because I felt like it
was really necessary

00:09:04.580 --> 00:09:06.500
if I wanted to be
more than just a cook.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:08.107
I can always be a
cook, and I think

00:09:08.107 --> 00:09:10.440
there are really, really good
cooks, even better than me

00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:11.480
maybe out there.

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:13.700
But their challenge is the
language, and most of them

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:17.010
don't take that time
to go out there and try

00:09:17.010 --> 00:09:20.450
to learn the language, which you
definitely need to communicate

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:22.070
with a lot of people.

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:27.140
So that's kind of how
I became what I'm now--

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:28.510
people say I am.

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:33.380
But it's just by working hard
in a smart way, and just--

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:35.136
so far, so good, so we'll see.

00:09:35.136 --> 00:09:41.380
SPEAKER 2: Well, you also said
that the cookbook and Nopalito,

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:44.240
the restaurant itself, is an
attempt to remember and honor

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:46.470
the way things were from--

00:09:46.470 --> 00:09:48.650
I'm guessing you meant
your childhood in all that.

00:09:48.650 --> 00:09:49.525
GONZALO GUZMAN: Yeah.

00:09:49.525 --> 00:09:53.030
It goes back, again,
to the same idea.

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:58.160
Everything from scratch
and not taking shortcuts.

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:02.810
And that's kind of
how the restaurant is.

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:06.380
Masa, but it's not just the masa
that we make in the restaurant.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:09.300
And I think that's probably
the only Mexican restaurant

00:10:09.300 --> 00:10:10.580
maybe in San Francisco still.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:14.260
I'm not quite sure, but
that we grind our own masa

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:17.800
and we do the whole process
that a lot of people don't do.

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:21.410
Their food is really good, some
of the Mexican restaurants,

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:27.620
but I think they still take all
the shortcuts that I was raised

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:28.930
not taking those shortcuts.

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:31.470
And that's kind of
what I meant by saying

00:10:31.470 --> 00:10:35.742
that you wake up in the
morning, you grind your own--

00:10:35.742 --> 00:10:37.700
I mean, you cook your
corn the day before then.

00:10:37.700 --> 00:10:42.405
I remember waking up, getting
this molino, that you now have.

00:10:42.405 --> 00:10:44.360
And then grind
this masa and then

00:10:44.360 --> 00:10:45.910
pass it through
the metate, which

00:10:45.910 --> 00:10:49.250
is another piece of equipment.

00:10:49.250 --> 00:10:52.220
And then to get it really
fine and make the tortillas.

00:10:52.220 --> 00:10:55.040
It's all these steps
that I feel like we do it

00:10:55.040 --> 00:10:58.240
at the restaurant on
a different scale.

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:02.140
Queso fresco, we will
make our own queso fresco.

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:04.695
Churizo or things like that
that we do at the restaurant,

00:11:04.695 --> 00:11:07.190
that if I was doing it at
home when I was little--

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:11.130
Not anymore, because
now they all buy it.

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:13.840
Because things change, and it's
been 20 years almost since I--

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.620
now there is electricity, and
there is water, and all that.

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:21.255
But I am trying to keep that
idea, and just on a different--

00:11:21.255 --> 00:11:21.992
in a city.

00:11:21.992 --> 00:11:23.450
Which makes it a
little hard, but I

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:29.267
think that's the challenge that,
hopefully, people appreciate.

00:11:29.267 --> 00:11:31.100
Again, that's what you
can find in the book.

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:33.710
You can make it as complicated
as you want it to be,

00:11:33.710 --> 00:11:35.346
or as simple as
you want it to be.

00:11:35.346 --> 00:11:36.470
You can just buy tortillas.

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:38.151
You don't have to
make your own masa.

00:11:38.151 --> 00:11:39.650
But just so you see
it there and see

00:11:39.650 --> 00:11:42.050
how much work it takes
to do a tortilla,

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:45.320
and appreciate more what
we do in the restaurant.

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:47.180
STACY ADIMONDO: And
this goes back to--

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:49.580
I mean, one of the first
stories Gonzalo told me

00:11:49.580 --> 00:11:53.720
when I met him was about a
typical day in their family

00:11:53.720 --> 00:11:54.930
life when he was growing up.

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:58.430
So his family owned
cornfields, and they'd walk,

00:11:58.430 --> 00:12:01.250
starting at 5:00 in the morning
before the sun got too hot

00:12:01.250 --> 00:12:03.630
and it was just
impossible to do anything.

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:05.910
Walked to the cornfields,
tend the cornfields,

00:12:05.910 --> 00:12:09.590
dry all the corn by
themselves from in the fields.

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:12.020
Take it back, and then
there was one corn grinder

00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:15.680
in his town of 400 people,
his village of 400 people.

00:12:15.680 --> 00:12:18.470
So this was not only a
ritual, but literally

00:12:18.470 --> 00:12:20.300
like pure sustenance
for them, where

00:12:20.300 --> 00:12:22.610
every dish was based off masa.

00:12:22.610 --> 00:12:25.370
Corn was just-- Gonzalo
says in the book,

00:12:25.370 --> 00:12:28.310
and I love this line, is that
he feels like he wouldn't feel

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:31.870
like a Mexican if there wasn't
corn in his house at all times.

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:33.570
GONZALO GUZMAN: And it's true.

00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:36.500
At home, I always have
masa or tortillas,

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:40.190
because I need to
have some of that.

00:12:40.190 --> 00:12:42.470
I grew up with it, and it's
part of my life already.

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:43.520
STACY ADIMONDO: Yeah,
and I think just

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:45.380
to think about taking
a shortcut, for him,

00:12:45.380 --> 00:12:47.330
is just absolutely insane.

00:12:47.330 --> 00:12:50.137
And I think, in
some ways, it takes

00:12:50.137 --> 00:12:52.220
a little bit of convincing
for the average person.

00:12:52.220 --> 00:12:54.680
The first time you hear about
the process of making masa

00:12:54.680 --> 00:12:57.080
from scratch, you're like,
I would love to do that.

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:00.080
And then you're like, oh,
there's a lot of stuff to that,

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.020
and I'm not sure I can really
fit that into my weeknight.

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:05.300
But something that I learned
in the process of making

00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:08.060
the book with him is
that it is a ritual,

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:11.670
and it's something that's
actually very simple at heart

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:13.190
and not difficult to learn.

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:14.840
And once you kind of
get used to having

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:17.030
that as part of
your pantry, as part

00:13:17.030 --> 00:13:19.280
of your staples of
cooking in your kitchen,

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:21.860
you make a big batch on Sunday
night and then that's that.

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:25.800
And you have it to use
in any number of ways

00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:27.050
throughout the week.

00:13:27.050 --> 00:13:30.020
And the way that I think
it's used in Mexico

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:31.590
is so eye-opening.

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:35.990
It's not just to press into a
tortilla and serve as a taco.

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:38.080
We have a whole section
on masa in the book,

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:42.260
and I work for a magazine
called Saveur that focuses

00:13:42.260 --> 00:13:44.710
on international cuisine.

00:13:44.710 --> 00:13:48.290
And we ended up doing
a six-page story on--

00:13:48.290 --> 00:13:49.720
actually I have it with me.

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:51.890
We did a six-page
story that ended up

00:13:51.890 --> 00:13:55.490
you know putting masa
on the cover and inside.

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:57.890
And everybody sort of thought,
is there really that much

00:13:57.890 --> 00:13:58.710
to say about it?

00:13:58.710 --> 00:13:59.480
And there is.

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:02.110
It's like all the different
types of corn that you can use.

00:14:02.110 --> 00:14:03.860
All the different ways
that you can use it

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:08.810
beyond tacos or quesedillas,
the words that everybody

00:14:08.810 --> 00:14:11.030
is sort of familiar with
with Mexican cuisine.

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:12.530
You can use it to thicken soups.

00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:16.130
You can use it to make a
number of antojitos, that

00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:18.387
are the Mexican streets foods.

00:14:18.387 --> 00:14:20.720
Gonzalo says that they used
to fry little nuggets of it,

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:22.370
kind of like gnocchi,
and just pop them

00:14:22.370 --> 00:14:23.454
as snacks and [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:23.454 --> 00:14:25.744
GONZALO GUZMAN: It's kind of
like the base for anything

00:14:25.744 --> 00:14:26.450
you can imagine.

00:14:26.450 --> 00:14:27.950
And it's just,
again, like Play-Doh.

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:30.080
You can make anything
or any figure you want.

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:31.080
So same thing with masa.

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:33.280
You can even eat
it as a dessert.

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:37.400
There is a recipe that
didn't make it to the book,

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:41.300
but it's a drink that is base
of masa, water, and sugar.

00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:42.590
A specific sugar.

00:14:42.590 --> 00:14:47.080
But, again, it's kind of like
if there is nothing else to it,

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:49.520
I think you will
survive with just masa.

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:52.710
That's how I see it, and
that's why it's so- to me,

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:56.300
it's so important
to have it with me.

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:58.850
But, again, it's
also for you guys

00:14:58.850 --> 00:15:00.815
if you wanted to play with it.

00:15:00.815 --> 00:15:02.690
Have some masa and start
playing with things,

00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:05.980
and you'll see you'll survive.

00:15:05.980 --> 00:15:07.460
