of unexpected ingredients

00:15:56.450 --> 00:15:58.580
that I don't think many
people would associate

00:15:58.580 --> 00:16:00.710
with Mexican right off the bat.

00:16:00.710 --> 00:16:03.650
Even just in the spice cabinet,
you might think of cumin,

00:16:03.650 --> 00:16:06.830
but you wouldn't necessarily
think of cloves, or anise,

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:11.300
or marjoram, or all
these beautiful, musty,

00:16:11.300 --> 00:16:13.700
and deeply-flavored
spices that go

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:17.460
into things like moles, and
sauces, and chili paste,

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:19.680
and braised meats.

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:23.420
So all of a sudden, once
you start noticing that,

00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:25.045
you taste the cuisine
very differently.

00:16:25.045 --> 00:16:26.544
You take a bite of
something and you

00:16:26.544 --> 00:16:29.119
think like, wow, this actually
has so many layers of flavors.

00:16:29.119 --> 00:16:31.160
Those spices are toasted
and then they're ground.

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:34.280
And then there are a number--
we have a whole section

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:36.160
on dried chilis in the book.

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:38.160
Because I think if you
think of Mexican cuisine,

00:16:38.160 --> 00:16:42.170
you think of jalapenos,
poblanos, serranos, maybe.

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:44.840
But those are the fresh, green
versions of these chilis,

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:49.520
and so many of them
are smoked, dried.

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:51.540
They come in so many
different flavors.

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:54.620
If you walk into a Mexican
market in San Francisco,

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:57.320
you'll see, literally,
a wall of dried chilis

00:16:57.320 --> 00:16:59.510
