then just go on your own
journey with that style

00:22:43.970 --> 00:22:48.080
once Gonzalo kind of gives
you the confidence to--

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:48.910
the base level.

00:22:48.910 --> 00:22:51.076
GONZALO GUZMAN: And keep
in mind that the first time

00:22:51.076 --> 00:22:53.230
that you do something,
it almost never

00:22:53.230 --> 00:22:55.230
will turn out the way you
wanted it to turn out.

00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:57.105
It takes some practice,
and that goes with me

00:22:57.105 --> 00:23:00.130
too whenever I'm trying and
some new dish that I kind of--

00:23:00.130 --> 00:23:04.144
I've seen it before in
Mexico, or I want to do it.

00:23:04.144 --> 00:23:05.810
It takes me two, or
three, or four times

00:23:05.810 --> 00:23:08.280
until I get it the
way I wanted it to do.

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:10.520
So I know in the pictures
it always looks nice,

00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:13.090
and when you do it, it
doesn't look just the same.

00:23:13.090 --> 00:23:15.530
But I think that
just keeping in mind

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:18.330
that that's going to be almost
the case with any cuisine,

00:23:18.330 --> 00:23:21.290
I guess, when you
try something new.

00:23:21.290 --> 00:23:24.250
So just don't be
afraid to not get it

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:26.000
right the first time,
and the second time,

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.270
and the third time, or
maybe even the fourth time.

00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:31.580
It's just like
everything, practice.

00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:35.569
The recipes are there just to
guide you through the process.

00:23:35.569 --> 00:23:37.610
But again, there's some
techniques here and there

00:23:37.610 --> 00:23:40.070
that you can have to
develop yourself as you

00:23:40.070 --> 00:23:41.295
practice with what recipe.

00:23:41.295 --> 00:23:42.170
STACY ADIMONDO: Yeah.

00:23:42.170 --> 00:23:46.070
We have a joke in the preface
of the book about my first time

00:23:46.070 --> 00:23:49.190
frying the salsa, which who
knew that that was even a thing.

00:23:49.190 --> 00:23:52.590
But you dump hot
salsa into hot oil,

00:23:52.590 --> 00:23:55.910
and you can guess what happens
if you choose the wrong pan.

00:23:55.910 --> 00:23:58.910
My entire backsplash
in my kitchen

00:23:58.910 --> 00:24:01.161
was like Jackson Pollock
from salsa a couple of times.

00:24:01.161 --> 00:24:02.868
GONZALO GUZMAN: The
trick is not to stop.

00:24:02.868 --> 00:24:04.050
Just put everything.

00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:06.020
Don't stop right there, because
that's when the-- you know.

00:24:06.020 --> 00:24:07.520
STACY ADIMONDO: It's
exactly the opposite

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:08.300
of what you would think.

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:10.091
All of a sudden, when
it starts sputtering,

00:24:10.091 --> 00:24:12.230
you probably want to pull
off and stop doing it.

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:13.891
But Gonzalo's like,
don't be afraid.

00:24:13.891 --> 00:24:16.390
Just dump the whole thing in
there and it's actually better.

00:24:16.390 --> 00:24:19.110
But I think at the
end of the day,

00:24:19.110 --> 00:24:22.700
even if it is
slightly imperfect,

00:24:22.700 --> 00:24:25.370
I still can't make a
perfect circle tortilla.

00:24:25.370 --> 00:24:27.610
I can't do it, and
I don't know why.

00:24:27.610 --> 00:24:29.160
But even if it is
slightly imperfect,

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:31.130
I think it just-- food
tastes better when it

00:24:31.130 --> 00:24:32.900
has a story behind it, really.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:37.100
And Gonzalo, every single
recipe in that book

00:24:37.100 --> 00:24:39.920
has a story about it, and some
little moment of education

00:24:39.920 --> 00:24:44.180
that gives you a window into
beautiful culture and cuisine

00:24:44.180 --> 00:24:44.790
in Mexico.

00:24:44.790 --> 00:24:47.390
And I think it's just
so much more satisfying

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:49.910
to sit down at your dinner
table and serve your friends

00:24:49.910 --> 00:24:51.530
and family that type of food.

00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:53.750
And say, here's the
background of it.

00:24:53.750 --> 00:24:56.240
I learned from this
amazing guy's story.

00:24:56.240 --> 00:24:58.760
And that, to me, is
what makes it special.

00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:03.940
SPEAKER 2: So what would you
say the overall goal is to reach

00:25:03.940 --> 00:25:05.190
people with through this book?

00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:07.106
What are you hoping
people will get out of it?

00:25:07.106 --> 00:25:10.110
GONZALO GUZMAN: I think it's
always been my goal just

00:25:10.110 --> 00:25:11.702
to kind of educate
people about food.

00:25:11.702 --> 00:25:14.160
And with this book, I think
that's what we're trying to do,

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:18.630
is to educate people more
about what Mexican food is,

00:25:18.630 --> 00:25:21.660
and what it takes--

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:25.530
what it takes,
again, to really--

00:25:25.530 --> 00:25:27.510
what we do at the
restaurant, and what

00:25:27.510 --> 00:25:28.720
I did when I was little.

00:25:28.720 --> 00:25:31.820
Again, it kind of
reflects my life,

00:25:31.820 --> 00:25:33.640
but at the same times,
Nopalito's life,

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:36.199
because that's what we've
been doing all the time.

00:25:36.199 --> 00:25:38.490
So, again, it's just to
educate people and kind of know

00:25:38.490 --> 00:25:41.450
more of what we do
at the restaurant.

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:45.300
And just to tell people that
it's not that easy when people

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:48.397
go into the place and
complain about the price

00:25:48.397 --> 00:25:49.230
that they're paying.

00:25:49.230 --> 00:25:50.688
Because I think
they have that idea

00:25:50.688 --> 00:25:52.110
with Chinese food
or Mexican food

00:25:52.110 --> 00:25:53.680
that it's always
going to be cheap.

00:25:53.680 --> 00:25:55.950
But if you look at the
steps, and the process,

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:57.720
and the ingredients
that we use here,

00:25:57.720 --> 00:26:00.306
we use all the fresh ingredients
that we use in this book

00:26:00.306 --> 00:26:01.180
or in the restaurant.

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:04.240
They're all local, so we work
with a lot of local farmers.

00:26:04.240 --> 00:26:05.670
We go to the farmers markets.

00:26:05.670 --> 00:26:08.970
Not myself, but Chef
Laurence goes, because I

00:26:08.970 --> 00:26:10.590
don't have enough time.

00:26:10.590 --> 00:26:12.480
But we kind of work
together to see.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:15.360
He'll tell me what's new, and
we will add it to the menu.

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:17.330
And that's kind of like,
again, how I grew up.

00:26:17.330 --> 00:26:21.630
Just by using what's in my
backyard, what we had there,

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:24.670
or we'll just grow it wild.

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:27.600
So the end is just I think
we're not trying to--

00:26:27.600 --> 00:26:30.052
personally, I'm not
trying to tell everyone,

00:26:30.052 --> 00:26:31.260
this is what Mexican food is.

00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:33.349
This is the best Mexican book.

00:26:33.349 --> 00:26:34.890
I think this is just
what Nopalito is

00:26:34.890 --> 00:26:37.170
right now, and part of my life.

00:26:37.170 --> 00:26:39.660
And hopefully, people really
appreciate more the restaurant

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:40.230
and enjoy.

00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:42.210
And again, this is
just one little piece

00:26:42.210 --> 00:26:45.820
of Mexican food from
the South, Veracruz.

00:26:45.820 --> 00:26:48.320
So there is so much
more about Mexican food,

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:50.820
and I'm sure there will be
another chef that will say,

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:53.280
oh this is Mexican food now.

00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:55.589
But, again, I know
that's going to happen.

00:26:55.589 --> 00:26:58.130
But I'm not trying to say that
this is the best Mexican food,

00:26:58.130 --> 00:26:58.670
I'm just--

00:26:58.670 --> 00:26:59.560
Mexican restaurant, I'm sorry.

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:01.893
STACY ADIMONDO: One thing you
must realize about Gonzalo

00:27:01.893 --> 00:27:04.430
is that he couldn't
possibly be more humble,

00:27:04.430 --> 00:27:07.470
so I'm here to do
his bragging for him.

00:27:07.470 --> 00:27:10.510
And it is the best
Mexican book, by the way.

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:12.660
GONZALO GUZMAN:
[INAUDIBLE], you guys.

00:27:12.660 --> 00:27:16.346
No, but honestly, you don't
see any flour tortillas there.

00:27:16.346 --> 00:27:17.970
And that's because
I grew up in a place

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:19.500
that there were no
flour tortillas.

00:27:19.500 --> 00:27:21.166
I didn't know there
were flour tortillas

00:27:21.166 --> 00:27:24.420
until I came to California.

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:26.625
So that wasn't till
I was 15 years old,

00:27:26.625 --> 00:27:28.486
that's when I finally
made flour tortillas.

00:27:28.486 --> 00:27:29.610
But that wasn't in my head.

00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:31.350
That wasn't in my food.

00:27:31.350 --> 00:27:34.870
That's all like north of
Mexico, but it's Mexican food.

00:27:37.884 --> 00:27:40.050
It is Mexican food, but
it's just a different state,

00:27:40.050 --> 00:27:42.420
different place, different--
it's still Mexico

00:27:42.420 --> 00:27:44.590
so again it's a little place.

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:48.150
But at the same time it's
what Nopalito is about.

00:27:48.150 --> 00:27:52.542
And, again, part of
my life there too.

00:27:52.542 --> 00:27:56.280
STACY ADIMONDO: I'm
in the food business,

00:27:56.280 --> 00:27:59.280
I write about food for
a living, and I probably

00:27:59.280 --> 00:28:01.890
would've thought I knew
something about Mexican cuisine

00:28:01.890 --> 00:28:03.120
before I met Gonzalo.

00:28:03.120 --> 00:28:06.270
And I sort of felt like, well,
yeah, I don't know everything,

00:28:06.270 --> 00:28:09.550
but I sort of get
the general concept.

00:28:09.550 --> 00:28:12.270
And something that Gonzalo says,
and we address in the book,

00:28:12.270 --> 00:28:15.600
is I think a lot of people
assume it's very heavy.

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:17.730
Everything's cooked in
lard, or deep-fried,

00:28:17.730 --> 00:28:19.747
or there's a side
of rice and beans

00:28:19.747 --> 00:28:20.830
on the side of everything.

00:28:20.830 --> 00:28:22.680
And it's a gut bomb,
and you kind of

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:24.720
like eat it when
you're hungover.

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:28.560
It's like really kind
of silly, and it all

00:28:28.560 --> 00:28:29.970
starts with the chips and salsa.

00:28:29.970 --> 00:28:34.920
And I very, very, quickly
learned that that was not true.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:37.800
And of course those foods
are a part of the cuisine,

00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:44.970
but it's a very fresh,
regional, varied cuisine.

00:28:44.970 --> 00:28:48.390
Something in the book that I
love is a chicken soup recipe.

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:52.710
And there's a big chipotle
chili floating on top of it,

00:28:52.710 --> 00:28:55.604
and there's homemade queso
fresco that's cut into cubes

00:28:55.604 --> 00:28:57.770
and put at the bottom of
it with chunks of avocados.

00:28:57.770 --> 00:29:00.350
So as you dip your
spoon in, there's

00:29:00.350 --> 00:29:03.540
this melty piece of cheese
at the bottom of your bowl.

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:07.307
It's just so wonderful, and
so nourishing, and so fresh,

00:29:07.307 --> 00:29:07.890
and different.

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:10.420
And I just didn't know
that that existed,

00:29:10.420 --> 00:29:12.300
even as a section
of Mexican food,

00:29:12.300 --> 00:29:14.460
which sounded so silly
to say in retrospect.

00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:16.260
But I think you
know a lot of people

00:29:16.260 --> 00:29:20.040
are missing that depth of
understanding the cuisine.

00:29:20.040 --> 00:29:23.310
So I think, at least,
I'm extremely honored

00:29:23.310 --> 00:29:25.410
to have been able to
help him tell this story,

00:29:25.410 --> 00:29:29.940
and to just be educated myself
to walk into a Mexican market

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:34.350
and be able to put some fun
ingredients on the countertop

00:29:34.350 --> 00:29:37.830
and just kind of be like,
yeah, I know what I'm doing.

00:29:37.830 --> 00:29:39.780
It's so empowering,
and it also just helps

00:29:39.780 --> 00:29:41.520
you connect to
this country that's

00:29:41.520 --> 00:29:46.020
our neighbors, and our people.

00:29:46.020 --> 00:29:48.990
So many of them are so
humble and hardworking,

00:29:48.990 --> 00:29:51.550
and they're not going
to brag for themselves.

00:29:51.550 --> 00:29:53.430
But I think there's
so much worth

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:57.120
uncovering in taking the time to
go learn about in this cuisine.

00:29:57.120 --> 00:30:00.660
So I'm very happy I
got to be part of it.

00:30:00.660 --> 00:30:02.710
GONZALO GUZMAN: Me too.

00:30:02.710 --> 00:30:05.455
And I've been happy
just to be around people

00:30:05.455 --> 00:30:11.880
that believe in me, and then
to help me to get this project.

00:30:11.880 --> 00:30:16.260
And now be chef/owner
of a couple restaurants.

00:30:16.260 --> 00:30:19.080
but again, there's so
many good cooks there,

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:21.004
but that's what they're missing.

00:30:21.004 --> 00:30:22.170
People that believe in them.

00:30:22.170 --> 00:30:25.290
And also, then, they need
to educate thier self

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:26.340
with a little more--

00:30:26.340 --> 00:30:29.180
by going, at least,
to learn the language.

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:33.690
Because that's one-- that's
something that they--

00:30:33.690 --> 00:30:35.940
If we don't do it, then we
cannot really do much here.

00:30:35.940 --> 00:30:37.606
Even if we're really
good cooks or we're

00:30:37.606 --> 00:30:41.380
really good with anything, we
have to take that extra step.

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:43.800
And that's what I'm
trying to prove, also.

00:30:43.800 --> 00:30:46.165
Myself, but to the
people around me.

00:30:46.165 --> 00:30:49.560
Kind of show them
that we can do it,

00:30:49.560 --> 00:30:53.040
but we also have to
put hard work on it.

00:30:53.040 --> 00:30:53.712
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:53.712 --> 00:30:57.139
Is there one dish that
you'd want everybody who

00:30:57.139 --> 00:30:58.430
walks into the restroom to try?

00:31:01.202 --> 00:31:03.510
GONZALO GUZMAN: Masa.

00:31:03.510 --> 00:31:06.240
So whatever you can
find with masa, try it.

00:31:06.240 --> 00:31:09.780
So that's 90% of our menu, 95%.

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:10.960
It's everything.

00:31:10.960 --> 00:31:14.440
Again, every dish
that you see there,

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:16.512
we're very proud of doing it.

00:31:16.512 --> 00:31:17.970
And I feel like if
it's there, it's

00:31:17.970 --> 00:31:21.792
because we felt it's tasty, and
it's good, and it's delicious.

00:31:21.792 --> 00:31:23.250
But again, you go
into a restaurant

00:31:23.250 --> 00:31:26.340
where we have other
cooks, and sometimes, they

00:31:26.340 --> 00:31:29.010
might forget to put
salt [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:29.010 --> 00:31:31.125
We try the food every
day, like every morning.

00:31:31.125 --> 00:31:32.140
We try all the dishes.

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:34.098
But still, that's still
happens, unfortunately.

00:31:34.098 --> 00:31:36.030
Like if I'm not there.

00:31:36.030 --> 00:31:37.740
If someone is not
looking at them,

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:39.910
there will be cook that
hopefully we don't have--

00:31:39.910 --> 00:31:45.650
but keep that in mind that
with as we can or I can,

00:31:45.650 --> 00:31:50.160
I try to just make sure
that everything tastes

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:51.390
really good for everyone.

00:31:51.390 --> 00:31:53.100
But, no, I don't really have--

00:31:53.100 --> 00:31:57.150
I mean, carnitas is
there just because people

00:31:57.150 --> 00:31:59.550
who doesn't love pork.

00:31:59.550 --> 00:32:01.580
And then they said it
is the best carnitas,

00:32:01.580 --> 00:32:05.600
but again, go and try it
and you make that call.

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:08.250
STACY ADIMONDO: Yeah, carnitas
made the cover for a reason.

00:32:08.250 --> 00:32:11.536
Something that I love is seeing
the rotating ceviche offerings

00:32:11.536 --> 00:32:12.160
that they have.

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:15.217
Because, again, that's part
of many cultures' cuisine.

00:32:15.217 --> 00:32:17.550
You can try a ceviche in a
lot of different restaurants,

00:32:17.550 --> 00:32:20.510
but I think I learned
something about Mexican ceviche

00:32:20.510 --> 00:32:23.550
from Gonzalo,
trying his versions.

00:32:23.550 --> 00:32:26.430
One has grated carrots
in it that I just

00:32:26.430 --> 00:32:31.090
thought was so special,
and unique, and unexpected.

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:33.300
He has a lot with--
some of them are red,

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:36.270
and have these sort of
like smoky, oily kind

00:32:36.270 --> 00:32:37.710
of sauces with them.

00:32:37.710 --> 00:32:39.690
And then others are
bright green, and fresh,

00:32:39.690 --> 00:32:40.500
and really vibrant.

00:32:40.500 --> 00:32:43.860
And kind of like sour
and puckery in the mouth.

00:32:43.860 --> 00:32:47.370
And, of course, his
chips are the best chips.

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:50.420
So it's really just a vehicle--

00:32:50.420 --> 00:32:52.640
an excuse to eat chips,
but they're beautiful.

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:54.140
GONZALO GUZMAN:
That's a good point,

00:32:54.140 --> 00:32:56.880
because a lot of people, when
they go and have cevivche,

00:32:56.880 --> 00:32:59.600
they always have in their
mind, tomato, onions, jalapeno,

00:32:59.600 --> 00:33:00.330
and fish.

00:33:00.330 --> 00:33:03.240
Overcooked fish.

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:04.740
To me, it's really
fresh everything.

00:33:04.740 --> 00:33:06.780
So it's whatever you
can find in-season.

00:33:06.780 --> 00:33:08.640
Right now it's asparagus.

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:11.280
Why not just using
that in your ceviche?

00:33:11.280 --> 00:33:12.060
If you cook it--

00:33:12.060 --> 00:33:13.420
SPEAKER 2: Which
you have right now.

00:33:13.420 --> 00:33:14.586
GONZALO GUZMAN: Not anymore.

00:33:14.586 --> 00:33:15.469
We just changed that.

00:33:15.469 --> 00:33:16.260
No, we still do it.

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:16.510
Sorry.

00:33:16.510 --> 00:33:17.218
We still have it.

00:33:17.218 --> 00:33:19.620
We just changed-- yeah.

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:22.830
You're supposed to use what
you can grow it yourself,

00:33:22.830 --> 00:33:23.790
or what's in season.

00:33:23.790 --> 00:33:26.490
And I think, why are you
using something else that

00:33:26.490 --> 00:33:29.730
is not really in
season if you have it?

00:33:29.730 --> 00:33:32.220
I don't know if it
makes sense, but just

00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:34.020
use what you have
instead of trying

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:37.744
to eat tomatoes when they're not
actually really good and sweet.

00:33:37.744 --> 00:33:40.160
Just wait until the season,
it's going to come back again.

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:42.784
STACY ADIMONDO: I think there's
a really neat component to when

00:33:42.784 --> 00:33:45.720
you go to Nopalito
about trying the dishes,

00:33:45.720 --> 00:33:47.280
and the way the
menu is laid out.

00:33:47.280 --> 00:33:50.280
Because unlike, I
think, many cuisines,

00:33:50.280 --> 00:33:53.190
you don't start with
a lettuce salad,

00:33:53.190 --> 00:33:56.010
and then move on to a main
entree, and then eat dessert.

00:33:56.010 --> 00:33:59.130
It's sort of like you kind of
choose your own adventure of,

00:33:59.130 --> 00:34:02.820
do you want to eat a
combination of street foods?

00:34:02.820 --> 00:34:04.570
A very casual meal
in Mexico, I think,

00:34:04.570 --> 00:34:07.200
is you eat a taco,
you to gordita.

00:34:07.200 --> 00:34:09.969
You eat a number of things that
the street vendors are making

00:34:09.969 --> 00:34:11.550
or that you're making at home.

00:34:11.550 --> 00:34:17.217
Or you eat these larger plates,
larger-format meals that are--

00:34:17.217 --> 00:34:18.925
when Gonzalo was
growing up, kind of more

00:34:18.925 --> 00:34:20.630
of a weekend thing, I think.

00:34:20.630 --> 00:34:22.743
When they'd have an animal and--

00:34:22.743 --> 00:34:25.560
GONZALO GUZMAN: Yeah.

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:27.690
I grew up eating
mostly vegetable,

00:34:27.690 --> 00:34:29.190
because meat was
really expensive.

00:34:29.190 --> 00:34:32.190
And that's the other reason why
I didn't eat meat that much.

00:34:32.190 --> 00:34:34.815
But we will eat the mole
sauce without the chicken,

00:34:34.815 --> 00:34:37.190
and it'll be still
really good mole.

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:39.230
But that was kind of the
reason, just because we

00:34:39.230 --> 00:34:40.796
wouldn't have access to--

00:34:40.796 --> 00:34:41.712
STACY ADIMONDO: Right.

00:34:42.212 --> 00:34:44.540
GONZALO GUZMAN: We'll go
and maybe kill an armadillo,

00:34:44.540 --> 00:34:45.829
make it into--

00:34:45.829 --> 00:34:49.840
Again, we will have to
go out there and hunt it.

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:51.100
That's kind of like--

00:34:51.100 --> 00:34:55.610
again, it's [INAUDIBLE],
but that's kind of why.

00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:58.110
STACY ADIMONDO: But it's neat
to navigate the menu, I think,

00:34:58.110 --> 00:34:59.651
at the restaurant
for the first time.

00:34:59.651 --> 00:35:01.860
And sort of say,
we're going to combine

00:35:01.860 --> 00:35:04.580
a number of different styles of
these smaller plates and street

00:35:04.580 --> 00:35:05.840
foods.

00:35:05.840 --> 00:35:09.410
There's very few that I
recognized off first glance.

00:35:09.410 --> 00:35:11.780
There was like one taco on
the menu, one quesedilla

00:35:11.780 --> 00:35:14.490
on the menu, and everything else
was these neat things that--

00:35:14.490 --> 00:35:17.734
I was like, I think I--
do I know what that is?

00:35:17.734 --> 00:35:19.400
It's just fun to kind
of go there and do

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:22.860
it one way or the other,
and eat a number of street

00:35:22.860 --> 00:35:24.180
foods and masa-based things.

00:35:24.180 --> 00:35:26.340
Or then try things
like the carnitas,

00:35:26.340 --> 00:35:30.965
or carne asada, or [INAUDIBLE],
some of the braised meats,

00:35:30.965 --> 00:35:32.090
and that kind of thing too.

00:35:32.090 --> 00:35:34.355
So you should probably just
go on a number of times

00:35:34.355 --> 00:35:36.692
to Nopalito and see
what works for you.

00:35:36.692 --> 00:35:38.900
GONZALO GUZMAN: We did a
little twist here and there,

00:35:38.900 --> 00:35:40.650
just because I know
it's not for everyone.

00:35:40.650 --> 00:35:45.350
But salads wasn't
part of my cuisine.

00:35:45.350 --> 00:35:47.990
When I grew up, my salad was
a slice of tomato, lettuce,

00:35:47.990 --> 00:35:49.870
and lime juice.

00:35:49.870 --> 00:35:52.020
But I know here, if I do
that, people will be like,

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:52.561
what is this?

00:35:52.561 --> 00:35:53.660
Or something.

00:35:53.660 --> 00:35:56.104
Again, for the
restaurants, we're

00:35:56.104 --> 00:35:58.520
going to have to have that
option also for the guests too.

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:00.260
So I kind of had to
add a couple of salads

00:36:00.260 --> 00:36:01.250
that I didn't grow up with.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:02.900
They're probably not
really authentic,

00:36:02.900 --> 00:36:06.260
but again, we cook for the
guests at the end, too.

00:36:06.260 --> 00:36:07.970
So I kind of have to
make it work so it's

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:10.271
a win-win for both sides.

00:36:10.271 --> 00:36:12.742
AUDIENCE: So first of all,
my wife and I love Nopalito.

00:36:12.742 --> 00:36:14.450
It's our favorite
restaurant in the city.

00:36:14.450 --> 00:36:15.230
GONZALO GUZMAN: Thank you.

00:36:15.230 --> 00:36:17.688
AUDIENCE: We got engaged about
a year ago in San Francisco,

00:36:17.688 --> 00:36:21.020
and the first place we walked
to was Nopalito, so we love it.

00:36:23.750 --> 00:36:25.550
You learned growing
up how to cook

00:36:25.550 --> 00:36:27.470
for yourself or for a family.

00:36:27.470 --> 00:36:31.160
How did you learn to scale that
to cooking for two restaurants?

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:33.210
GONZALO GUZMAN: School.

00:36:33.210 --> 00:36:34.290
Yeah.

00:36:34.290 --> 00:36:39.660
Again, that was-- it's funny.

00:36:39.660 --> 00:36:43.130
I always tried to
learn something new,

00:36:43.130 --> 00:36:45.410
and actually just
two years ago, I just

00:36:45.410 --> 00:36:49.100
graduated from my GED,
high school diploma.

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:51.960
Which, again, I didn't go to
school in Mexico or anything.

00:36:51.960 --> 00:36:54.290
Just here, so it was
also at city college.

00:36:54.290 --> 00:36:56.000
But math was one
of those classes

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:57.650
that I took two
semesters, because I

00:36:57.650 --> 00:36:58.850
wasn't really good at it.

00:36:58.850 --> 00:37:01.310
And I'm still not good at it,
but I understand the basics

00:37:01.310 --> 00:37:03.770
that I need for cooking.

00:37:03.770 --> 00:37:07.190
So that is kind of what
helped me to just scale it up.

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:09.380
Because my co-chef,
which, again, I

00:37:09.380 --> 00:37:12.061
learned a lot from him,
and he's part of this book.

00:37:12.061 --> 00:37:14.310
Because most of these recipes,
we worked them together

00:37:14.310 --> 00:37:17.120
with Jose Ramos.

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:20.950
But that was his challenge
too, like, we need 24 quarts

00:37:20.950 --> 00:37:25.575
of salsa for tonight, but
our recipe says 1 quart.

00:37:25.575 --> 00:37:27.080
So what do we do?

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:31.310
So again, that pushed myself to
go to school whenever I could

00:37:31.310 --> 00:37:33.720
and just to take math.

00:37:33.720 --> 00:37:35.430
And that's kind of how I did it.

00:37:35.430 --> 00:37:37.020
And same thing goes
for don't now I

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:39.470
have to manage people instead
of just me, and cooking.

00:37:39.470 --> 00:37:43.870
Being by myself, cooking for the
people and being on the line.

00:37:43.870 --> 00:37:46.070
So I knew now that I
needed to work with people,

00:37:46.070 --> 00:37:48.680
and that's another challenge
working in a restaurant,

00:37:48.680 --> 00:37:49.730
is managing.

00:37:49.730 --> 00:37:52.670
So funny enough, I took one
semester of psychology too,

00:37:52.670 --> 00:37:53.170
just--

00:37:53.170 --> 00:37:55.560
I don't know, but I
felt like that will--

00:37:55.560 --> 00:38:00.340
And again, but going back
to the question, yes,

00:38:00.340 --> 00:38:02.529
and I went to school
for basic math

00:38:02.529 --> 00:38:04.070
that you probably
already understand.

00:38:04.070 --> 00:38:06.682
But just using that as--

00:38:06.682 --> 00:38:08.930
AUDIENCE: So I've always
wanted to go to Nopalito,

00:38:08.930 --> 00:38:10.850
but I have these
little rugrats that

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:13.610
hang out with me all the time.

00:38:13.610 --> 00:38:15.710
Do you feel like your
restaurant has options

00:38:15.710 --> 00:38:18.440
that are accessible for kids,
or if not kids, people that

00:38:18.440 --> 00:38:20.270
have a less-adventurous palate?

00:38:20.270 --> 00:38:23.015
What would you recommend?

00:38:23.015 --> 00:38:25.140
GONZALO GUZMAN: Well,
there's always rice and beans

00:38:25.140 --> 00:38:28.160
and cheese quesedillas for kids.

00:38:28.160 --> 00:38:29.000
But I have two kids.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:31.040
I have a boy and a girl.

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:32.540
Myself, I push them
to eat anything.

00:38:32.540 --> 00:38:34.165
So if they come
with me, honestly,

00:38:34.165 --> 00:38:37.050
it's like, here, you
eat some ceviche.

00:38:37.050 --> 00:38:38.240
You eat some [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:38.240 --> 00:38:43.640
But we have the options of
rice, beans, cheese quesedilla,

00:38:43.640 --> 00:38:45.129
side of chicken.

00:38:45.129 --> 00:38:46.670
Things that we kind
of know they're--

00:38:46.670 --> 00:38:47.540
STACY ADIMONDO:
Well, and I think

00:38:47.540 --> 00:38:49.539
some of the dishes that
maybe sound like they're

00:38:49.539 --> 00:38:54.770
going to be complicated or spicy
actually have a sweet side too.

00:38:54.770 --> 00:38:58.590
So like mole, I couldn't
imagine a kid not liking mole,

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:02.240
like licking their
fingers and making a mess.

00:39:02.240 --> 00:39:05.150
I think some of the
soups are really fun.

00:39:05.150 --> 00:39:06.650
There's a soup that has--

00:39:06.650 --> 00:39:08.110
it sort of looks like--

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:10.160
I kind of think of it
as the Mexican ramen.

00:39:10.160 --> 00:39:12.315
It's got noodles,
and chicken, and--

00:39:12.315 --> 00:39:14.440
GONZALO GUZMAN: Which is
not on the menu right now.

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:16.190
STACY ADIMONDO: Not
on the menu right now.

00:39:16.190 --> 00:39:20.450
But there's this fun
stuff, and it's colorful.

00:39:20.450 --> 00:39:22.760
I find that the
restaurant is often

00:39:22.760 --> 00:39:24.500
filled with families and kids.

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:26.960
I think it's a real
community that is loyal to

00:39:26.960 --> 00:39:28.010
and loves Nopalito.

00:39:28.010 --> 00:39:32.333
And it's definitely kind
of come one, come all menu.

00:39:32.333 --> 00:39:33.920
GONZALO GUZMAN: Chips and guac.

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:35.555
I mean, kids love that.

00:39:35.555 --> 00:39:38.152
I start by that, and then
I think-- slowly I've

00:39:38.152 --> 00:39:39.610
seen families that
have been coming

00:39:39.610 --> 00:39:42.950
to the restaurant for
now a few years already.

00:39:42.950 --> 00:39:45.260
When kids will just go
and order rice and beans,

00:39:45.260 --> 00:39:48.597
and little by little,
parents started pushing them

00:39:48.597 --> 00:39:49.430
with something else.

00:39:49.430 --> 00:39:51.346
And now they're like,
oh, I love your ceviche.

00:39:51.346 --> 00:39:53.610
I'm like, okay.

00:39:53.610 --> 00:39:55.610
I think it's a great
first opportunity for you

00:39:55.610 --> 00:39:56.945
to have your kids try that.

00:39:56.945 --> 00:39:58.750
And some of them get
addicted, actually.

00:39:58.750 --> 00:40:00.310
They start liking it.

00:40:00.310 --> 00:40:02.974
You'll see they like it more
than you will, probably.

00:40:02.974 --> 00:40:05.878
Yeah.

00:40:05.878 --> 00:40:07.820
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:09.550
So speaking of the
next generation,

00:40:09.550 --> 00:40:11.970
what are your future plans?

00:40:11.970 --> 00:40:13.940
Are there are going
to be more Nopalitos?

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:15.580
What else are you going to do?

00:40:15.580 --> 00:40:16.800
No, no more Nopalitos.

00:40:16.800 --> 00:40:21.100
I think there's one Nopalito,
or now, is kind of two.

00:40:21.100 --> 00:40:24.850
But those two make one.

00:40:24.850 --> 00:40:27.400
Definitely, I don't think
there will be another Nopalito

00:40:27.400 --> 00:40:28.480
restaurant.

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:30.970
We're not trying
to build a chain.

00:40:30.970 --> 00:40:33.034
That's what I think--

00:40:33.034 --> 00:40:34.450
my partner is right
here, actually

00:40:34.450 --> 00:40:35.590
will tell you that too.

00:40:35.590 --> 00:40:41.380
But definitely, there
is a things in my head.

00:40:41.380 --> 00:40:43.840
Hopefully, trying
to think of another

00:40:43.840 --> 00:40:48.840
place where we can do
Mexican/California food.

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:51.580
Kind of mix not really Mexican,
because I feel like this one

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:54.370
is Mexican food authentic
as much as we can.

00:40:54.370 --> 00:40:57.670
But I kind of want to get
into that of like maybe--

00:40:57.670 --> 00:41:01.330
I don't know, different concept
of mixing California, which

00:41:01.330 --> 00:41:04.900
have European and
French, and all this.

00:41:04.900 --> 00:41:08.950
But being Mexican ingredients
based off that place.

00:41:08.950 --> 00:41:11.440
But, again, that's just
in the head right now.

00:41:11.440 --> 00:41:14.690
There is nothing that
is happening yet.

00:41:14.690 --> 00:41:15.460
But, yeah.

00:41:15.460 --> 00:41:18.800
AUDIENCE: The idea is
of another cookbook?

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:20.587
GONZALO GUZMAN: No.

00:41:20.587 --> 00:41:22.920
STACY ADIMONDO: What about
the other half of the recipes

00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:23.920
that you mentioned?

00:41:24.200 --> 00:41:25.616
GONZALO GUZMAN:
Oh, they're there.

00:41:25.616 --> 00:41:27.136
They're in the restaurant.

00:41:27.136 --> 00:41:27.949
Oh, no.

00:41:27.949 --> 00:41:29.490
I don't think so,
but you never know.

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:31.000
So I'm pretty open to whatever.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:33.125
STACY ADIMONDO: Well, and
I think the cookbook just

00:41:33.125 --> 00:41:34.420
becomes a tool.

00:41:34.420 --> 00:41:36.160
It's a conversation
starter, I think.

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:40.247
And that's something a
lot of chefs get very--

00:41:40.247 --> 00:41:42.580
They want to have everything
be perfect with their book,

00:41:42.580 --> 00:41:45.421
and they want to make sure
everybody covers it and what

00:41:45.421 --> 00:41:45.920
not

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:50.050
But I think this book
just has its own spirit

00:41:50.050 --> 00:41:56.500
of communal education,
sharing, getting the word out.

00:41:56.500 --> 00:41:59.650
Gonzalo kind of spreads the love
in the book, and he's not like,

00:41:59.650 --> 00:42:00.340
me, me, me.

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:00.850
My food.

00:42:00.850 --> 00:42:01.360
My food.

00:42:01.360 --> 00:42:03.970
It's sort of like,
this region in Mexico,

00:42:03.970 --> 00:42:07.600
or, the people who work
with me, or just, you

00:42:07.600 --> 00:42:09.230
should know this
about our culture.

00:42:09.230 --> 00:42:12.640
So I think the exciting thing
about the book coming out

00:42:12.640 --> 00:42:14.710
is just that it gives
another platform

00:42:14.710 --> 00:42:17.620
to talk about all this
beautiful background and story

00:42:17.620 --> 00:42:19.540
that I think a lot of
people don't know about

00:42:19.540 --> 00:42:20.420
and should hear.

00:42:20.420 --> 00:42:21.920
GONZALO GUZMAN:
Yeah, but it's true.

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:25.390
I'm not really
inventing anything new.

00:42:25.390 --> 00:42:27.520
All these things, someone
is making them in Mexico.

00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:31.780
I'm just trying to make
it work for San Francisco,

00:42:31.780 --> 00:42:34.090
and using what's around here.

00:42:34.090 --> 00:42:37.132
But, again, you see
carnitas-- and I'm not

00:42:37.132 --> 00:42:39.340
saying this is the only
place you're going to see it.

00:42:39.340 --> 00:42:43.000
You go to Mexico and you're
going to see all different--

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:44.830
what we're doing is
just the techniques,

00:42:44.830 --> 00:42:48.670
and fixing little
things here and there.

00:42:48.670 --> 00:42:52.040
Making it just taste
better, even if possible.

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:54.842
So that's what it's about.

00:42:54.842 --> 00:42:55.716
SPEAKER 2: All right.

00:42:55.716 --> 00:42:57.702
Well, with that,
thank you guys both.

00:42:58.202 --> 00:42:59.285
STACY ADIMONDO: Thank you.

00:42:59.287 --> 00:43:00.870
SPEAKER 2: And thank
you everyone else

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:02.380
for coming and joining us.

00:43:02.380 --> 00:43:02.980
STACY ADIMONDO: Thank you, guys.

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:04.063
GONZALO GUZMAN: Thank you.

00:43:04.063 --> 00:43:07.230
[APPLAUSE]

